„Yes, Captain. You should be on your way by now, they were still at the mess hall to pick up their rations.“  Exactly at 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
„We are moving to the forward deployment base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the later attack on Ianlos, to drive out the rebels. There we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains,” explained Shaw. „Mount up and move out to your squads.”
The company dispersed into their respective squads, and the soldiers were assigned by the non-commissioned officers to the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days earlier, but knew little about them. He sat on the side and let his legs dangle while he adjusted his backpack and the radio equipment connected to his headphones and throat microphone.
„Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?“, asked Nemic after they had settled in.
„Do you mean the rooster he stole?“ Cohren remembered the morning they let the animal walk on a farm. „Yes, I think so.”
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he noticed the movement of a small hen, searching the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
„Yes, he is still with him,“ answered Cohren, as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
„All tanks are moving out,“ spoke the commander slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the convoy of tanks and Strykers roared to life as they began moving. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding in, jolted as the brake was released and they reformed into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Due to the winter storms, the marshy areas had frozen and the woods were covered in snow, yet the mud was everywhere.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. „Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?“
„Yes, Operation Firestorm,“ answered Cohren. „We thought the matter would be settled in a few weeks, but we underestimated it.“
„Unterschätzt ist stark untertrieben“, mischte sich Nemic in das Gespräch ein. „Auf ihr Waffenarsenal und die Masse an Soldaten waren wir nicht vorbereitet. Sie haben die UFS Revenant in den ersten zwei Wochen zerstört und erst letzten Monat die Erebus. Wir sollten sie sogar auf unserem Weg sehen.“
„Ich stehe fest an der Seite der Föderation“, sagte Orson trotzig. „Ich lasse mir von diesen Terroristen keine Angst machen.“
„Das sagst du jetzt. Aber ich hab gesehen, dass die meisten achtzehnjährigen Rekruten wie du ganz schnell in Deckung gehen, sobald sie einen Schuss hören“, erklärte Craith.
„Das werden wir ja sehen“, sagte Cohren lachend. Orson stellte das Gespräch ein.
„Exodus XO, Exodus CO“, knisterte Cohrens Funkgerät. „Wir empfangen Wärmesignaturen, gute 300 Meter entfernt, 20 Grad rechts.“
Cohren climbed up the tank and put on his special goggles. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could see the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," answered Cohren over his larynx microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't tell," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, fire only when under fire. Let's lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like thermal signatures took shape. As they came closer, one of them ran off hastily to get something. Immediately, she returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, taking up shooting positions.
“We have enemy contact,” Shaw called over the radio, as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hilltop. While the tanks were under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket streaked past and hit behind the formation, exploding and scattering debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another struck sideways into a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition exploded into the air.
“Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire at will,” shouted the lead tank commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew toward the hilltop and exploded, sending mud and rock into the air.
“Send the Sentis in,” called Knoxx, who was observing the hilltop with a binocular. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier emerged, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they sprinted ahead. They carried their weapons on their backs.
“Kill or capture?” asked Craith as they watched.
“It looks like capture,” assumed Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke cloud. Screams and gunfire echoed from the hilltop, but quickly faded. A short time later, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left marks in the ground. After returning to the safety of the column, they threw the figure onto the ground. She moaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure who was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the sentinels. „How many?“
„Three dead, Sir“, answered the sentinel. „The rest have fled on foot.“
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. „Get this guy out of my sight!“
